Today, Nicholas Soames, a very senior politician, has called for a Government of national unity (according to Anna Soubry on BBC Radio 4 this morning) which is interesting: it tells us the mess the Conservatives and Labour are in, and the gridlock that parliament is in. As the Chequers plan of last week is now in tatters, there is no way forward as it is highly unlikely to make it through parliament. This leaves Teresa May in a significant bind: she cant move forward, but neither can she move back (either to a more Remain stance or a more Brexiteer stance as the opposing stance immediately undermines her). She is in an impossible situation. So the possible options facing the country are:
1) Teresa May carries on as is - to nowhere; as things are she is not going to get her plan through parliament so this seems a pointless strategy; however she may just hang on in the hope that something changes over the summer (to speculate on what would take too long here); i think there is a low probability of her carrying on until October as things must be wearing her down - however this could move to medium probability over the summer as things settle down and she works on newer strategies. She is a very resilient woman and may just need a breather before she launches back into the fray. At the moment she must be feeling very frazzled, and it has to be said her health is not the best. 
2) Teresa May realises that she is at a dead-end and resigns to be replaced by either a Conservative Brexiteer (which will be followed by a Conservative meltdown as Remainer Conservatives won't stand for it so are likely to vote against him or her in parliament leading to an election and probable Labour government) or Remainer (in which case more of the same as under May, say for another 6 months); a Brexiteer replacement is unlikely as there isn't enough support for one; high probability;
3) May may be forced from power if there are elections should the Conservative Brexiteers bring down the government which, counter-productively, it looks like they are increasingly inclined to do should she not bend to their will; this would be counter-productive as it would lead to a Labour government and the Conservative Brexiteers would lose control of the process, so it would seem unlikely, but as a last resort, who knows? I wouldn't rule out Labour promising them a full Brexit in order to bring this about; low probability;
4) A government of national unity is formed which looks unlikely as Labour front bench are unlikely to support the idea as is Teresa May as it would imply a lack of confidence in her leadership; so, this is only likely to happen after Teresa May as gone.
5) A referendum on hard Brexit or soft Brexit; remaining is no longer an option. A referendum is only likely to happen after Teresa May has gone. My best guess is that Teresa May resigns and a Remainer Conservative takes her place ushering in either a government of national unity and/or referendum. The probability of her being forced from power is remote. The only circumstance under which she is likely to stay is if parliament were to rally round in the belief that all the remaining options are unacceptable. In the meantime the clock is ticking. Something is likely to give very soon.

Putting some structure in my forecast, the possible states of the world are: 1) No leadership contest in the Conservative party, T. May remains in office;
2) There is a leadership challenge, but T. May wins it;
3) T. May is challenged for the leadership and loses (or decides not to run);
4) No challenge, but T. May decides to leave for other reasons;
5) There are new elections and someone else from the Tories ends up the PM;
6) New elections, and someone from Labor becomes the PM;
7) New elections, and someone from a party other than Conservative or Labor is the PM. Starting from the end, I am ruling out new elections (outcomes 5), 6), and 7)). This is entirely in the Tories' hands and they agree that new elections can only lead to loss of MP seats.  Outcome 1) is, I think, most likely (53%). May does not want to leave and most of the party seems reluctantly behind her, if only for lack of better candidates.  Outcome 2) is not unlikely as well - I put 25%. Already 40 of the hard-Brexiteers are clamoring for May's head, and if this number gets to 48, there will be a contest. Still, both the center and the soft-Brexiteers would likely support May, so she has a better than 50/50 chance to win such a contest if she chooses to run.   For outcome (3), I put 20%. This will materialize if May decides not to run, or if some significant cataclysm makes her very unpopular. There is plenty of time for this to happen by Oct 1. Finally, for outcome (4) I put 2 percent. Although May's health is not perfect, so far it hasn't interfered with her ability to work.
